There’s a hush that settles over the world just before dawn, a gentle pause between the end of one day and the beginning of another. In these early hours, the city breathes differently. The streets, usually humming with the rush of cars and the chatter of people, are nearly empty. The only sounds are the distant call of a bird, the soft whir of a delivery van, and the occasional sigh of wind through the trees.

I love the way the light changes at this hour. It’s softer, more golden, painting the rooftops and windows with a warm glow. There’s a sense of possibility in the air, as if the world is holding its breath, waiting for someone to step outside and claim the day. Sometimes, I sit by the window with a cup of tea, watching the sky lighten, feeling the weight of the night slowly lift.

Early mornings are a gift—a quiet space where thoughts can settle and intentions can be set. It’s a time for reflection, for small rituals, for appreciating the simple beauty of a new beginning. And though the world wakes up soon enough, those first, gentle moments belong to anyone willing to greet the day before the rush begins.

